{{italic title}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file = Jimson Weed by Georgia O'Keeffe.jpg | painting_alignment = | image_size = 250px | title = Jimson Weed | alt = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = [[Georgia O'Keeffe]] | year = 1936 | type = [[Oil painting|Oil]] on [[linen]] | height_metric = | width_metric = | length_metric = | height_imperial = 70 | width_imperial = 83.5 | length_imperial = | diameter__metric = | diameter_imperial = | imperial_unit = in | metric_unit = cm | city = [[Indianapolis]] | museum = [[Indianapolis Museum of Art]] | coordinates = | owner = }}
'''''Jimson Weed''''' is an oil on linen painting by American artist [[Georgia O'Keeffe]] from 1936, located in the [[Indianapolis Museum of Art]], which is in [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]], United States. It depicts four large blossoms of [[jimson weed]], or datura. A similar work by O'Keeffe, '''''Jimson Weed/White Flower No. 1''''', was sold by the [[Georgia O'Keeffe Museum]] at auction to [[Walmart]] heiress [[Alice Walton]] in 2014 for $44,405,000, more than tripling the previous world record for auction price of a piece by a female artist.
==Description== O'Keeffe reiterated the pinwheel-shaped flowers' structure in the tight placement of the four blossoms in the painting. Her use of rhythmic light and shade and a simplified palette underscores their fresh, simple beauty.<ref>{{cite web|last=Goodman|first=Melissa|title=Datura flowers in art and images|url=http://www.flickriver.com/photos/96683394@N00/3938263553/|work=The Gifted Photographer|accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref>
==Historical information== O'Keeffe was immensely fond of jimson weed, ignoring its seeds' toxicity and allowing it to flourish around her patio.<ref>{{cite book|last=Drohojowska-Philp|first=Hunter|title=Full Bloom: The Art and Life of Georgia O'Keeffe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SQzD7mwpPgQC&pg=PA376-IA20&lpg=PA376-IA20&dq=georgia+o%27keeffe+jimson+weed+1936&source=bl&ots=mLJcHP6su5&sig=MOQHdO9fD7w3ps7ApB5c-bvm4-o&hl=en&sa=X&ei=viSQUJUEqLfLAdbBgNgD&ved=0CFgQ6AEwCTgU#v=onepage&q=georgia%20o%27keeffe%20jimson%20weed%201936&f=false|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|accessdate=14 November 2012|page=376|year=2004}}</ref> She paid tribute to the bloom in this painting, originally entitled ''Miracle Flower''. ''Jimson Weed'' was commissioned by cosmetics magnate [[Elizabeth Arden]] for the new Gymnasium Moderne of her [[Fifth Avenue]] Salon in [[New York City]]. Placed in the exercise room, the unfurling blossoms were meant to encourage clients in their stretches. Arden paid the exorbitant sum of $10,000 for the largest floral composition O'Keeffe would ever create.<ref name=lee>{{cite book|last1=Lee|first1=Ellen Wardwell|last2=Robinson|first2=Anne|title=Indianapolis Museum of Art: Highlights of the Collection|publisher=Indianapolis Museum of Art|location=Indianapolis|year=2005|isbn=0936260777}}</ref> <!--Should include other details such as the symbolism to environment/ relevance to what was happening in society at the time. -->
===Acquisition=== The painting was acquired by the IMA in 1997, a gift of [[Eli Lilly and Company]], who had acquired it from Arden's salon in 1971. It is currently on view in the Paine American Modernism Gallery and has the accession number 1997.131.<ref name=ima>{{cite web|title=Jimson Weed|url=http://www.imamuseum.org/art/collections/artwork/jimson-weed-okeeffe-georgia|publisher=[[Indianapolis Museum of Art]]|accessdate=14 November 2012}}</ref>
