{{Infobox musical composition | Name = ''Symphony No. 2'' | Composer = [[Philip Glass]] | Form = [[Symphony]] | Duration = 40 minutes<ref name="ref1">[http://www.philipglass.com/music/compositions/symphony_2.php Philip Glass: Music: Symphony No. 2]</ref> | Period = [[Contemporary classical music|Contemporary]] | Style = [[Postmodern music|Postmodern]], [[Minimalist music|minimalist]] | Publisher = Dunvagen Music Publishers<ref name="ref1" /> | Premiere_date = {{Start date|1994|10|15}} | Premiere_location = | Premiere_conductor = [[Dennis Russell Davies]]<ref name="ref1" /> | Premiere_performers = [[Brooklyn Philharmonic|Brooklyn Philharmonic Orchestra]] }} [[Philip Glass]]' '''second symphony''' was commissioned by [[Brooklyn Academy of Music]]. It was first performed on October 15, 1994, by the [[Brooklyn Philharmonic Orchestra]], conducted by [[Dennis Russell Davies]].
==Scoring and structure== The work is scored for [[piccolo]], two [[flute]]s, two [[oboe]]s doubling [[English horn]], [[E-flat clarinet]], two [[clarinet|B-flat clarinets]], [[bass clarinet|bass/contrabass clarinet]], two [[bassoon]]s, four [[french horn|horns]], three [[trumpet]]s, three [[trombone]]s, [[tuba]], four percussionists, piano, harp, and strings.<ref name="ref2">[http://www.chesternovello.com/Default.aspx?TabId=2432&State_3041=2&workId_3041=6353# Philip Glass: Symphony No. 2]</ref> It has three continuous movements with contrasting themes and lasts approximately 40 minutes.
Glass commented on his use of polyphony in the work that "The great experiments of polytonality carried out in the 1930s and 40s show that there's still a lot of work to be done in that area. Harmonic language and melodic language can coexist closely or at some calculated distance, and their relationship can be worked out in terms of either coexisting harmonies or ambiguous harmonies...I'm more interested in the ambiguous qualities that can result from polytonality — how what you hear depends on how you focus your ear, how a listener's perception of tonality can vary in the fashion of an optical illusion. We're not talking about inventing a new language, but rather inventing new perceptions of existing languages."<ref>Programme notes to the 1998 recording on [http://www.philipglass.com/music/recordings/symphony_2.php Nonesuch Records]</ref>
